It's officially logged. I have 2.3 flight hours ^_^
#TeaganAir
If I had to describe what it's like to fly a small aircraft, I would say it's like a mix between a motorcycle/quadrac and a boat 4,000 feet in the air.
On the ground, you feel very fast. Everything is somewhat unstable on the ground, hence motorcycle/quadrac.
And if you didn't know: you steer an airplane on the ground with your feet, not with the control stick. Rudders and brakes. It's not a car.
In the air, it's wobbly and one floats a bit. It feels like being in a boat on water. One can steer it, but sometimes a wave throws one off course, so one has to get used to the sea motion, just in the air.
Another random detail:
Flying is physically demanding. My back and my legs hurt today as if I had been at the gym.
This is not like a Sunday outing in the car. It is more of a sport than a leisurely ride, in my newly gained opinion.
A lovely Saturday, dear ones. Welcome at 4,000 feet.
Tomorrow I'll go again. Then we'll practice stall recovery and slow flight.
Today the weather was turbulent, but it was lots of fun. We practiced slow flight and stall recovery. Once we had a ground speed of only 16 mph at an airspeed of 65.
It was a beautiful clear day, a bit misty higher up, but still beautiful.
Data-Track from FlightAware.
